00:01:34.842 --> 00:01:35.800
DAVID BARRY: I'm sorry.

00:01:35.800 --> 00:01:36.800
HEATHER BOUSHEY: No, no.

00:01:36.800 --> 00:01:38.740
It's always so like, oh golly.

00:01:38.740 --> 00:01:40.990
DAVID BARRY: Well, I thought
would jump Right into it.

00:01:40.990 --> 00:01:43.300
So you discussed
throughout the book,

00:01:43.300 --> 00:01:46.540
that the success of our economy
involves more than just success

00:01:46.540 --> 00:01:49.450
in the business sector, which is
a little different than the way

00:01:49.450 --> 00:01:52.720
most people, both in the
business community and outside

00:01:52.720 --> 00:01:55.420
of it, think of the economy.

00:01:55.420 --> 00:01:57.400
Could you describe
for us your vision

00:01:57.400 --> 00:02:00.010
of who the important
actors in the economy are,

00:02:00.010 --> 00:02:04.000
and what this more
comprehensive picture means

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:07.627
for how we should think about
assessing a successful economy?

00:02:07.627 --> 00:02:09.460
HEATHER BOUSHEY: Yeah,
happy to start there.

00:02:09.460 --> 00:02:11.918
First of all, thank you so much
for inviting me here today.

00:02:11.918 --> 00:02:14.940
This is really fun and just
it's a pleasure to be here.

00:02:14.940 --> 00:02:17.420
And welcome to all of you.

00:02:17.420 --> 00:02:20.926
And so in the book, I
talk a lot about thinking

00:02:20.926 --> 00:02:22.300
about what's good
for the economy

00:02:22.300 --> 00:02:25.090
and what we think actually
makes the economy grow.

00:02:25.090 --> 00:02:29.440
And a lot of times when
you talk to people,

00:02:29.440 --> 00:02:32.045
it really sort of transcends
political ideology.

00:02:32.045 --> 00:02:34.420
When you talk to people about
what they think is actually

00:02:34.420 --> 00:02:36.560
good for the economy,
you get this story

00:02:36.560 --> 00:02:40.120
that is very much a
supply side story.

00:02:40.120 --> 00:02:42.580
It's about well, when costs
are low for businesses.

00:02:42.580 --> 00:02:44.890
When you know wages are low,
they can hire more people.

00:02:44.890 --> 00:02:48.715
Or if there's less regulations
that mean that businesses

00:02:48.715 --> 00:02:49.840
have to jump through hoops.

00:02:49.840 --> 00:02:52.480
These are all things that
allow businesses to grow

00:02:52.480 --> 00:02:55.870
and that therefore is what we
need to do as policymakers,

00:02:55.870 --> 00:02:58.930
because that's what's
good for the economy.

00:02:58.930 --> 00:03:01.040
And that all may
be totally true.

00:03:01.040 --> 00:03:04.060
In fact, for any
individual business owner,

00:03:04.060 --> 00:03:05.894
those are actually very
important questions.

00:03:05.894 --> 00:03:07.601
You have to think
about your bottom line.

00:03:07.601 --> 00:03:10.100
You have to think about how
you're running your business.

00:03:10.100 --> 00:03:12.190
But when you step back
and think of the role

00:03:12.190 --> 00:03:14.650
of what policymakers
need to be thinking about

00:03:14.650 --> 00:03:16.540
or what economists
think about, you

00:03:16.540 --> 00:03:20.710
have to think of not just that
narrow business perspective.

00:03:20.710 --> 00:03:23.510
That's just one slice
of the bigger picture.

00:03:23.510 --> 00:03:24.190
Right?

00:03:24.190 --> 00:03:26.190
And so even sort of
thinking about the business,

00:03:26.190 --> 00:03:30.010
it's like, an employer has to
think about where they're going

00:03:30.010 --> 00:03:31.450
to get talented people to hire.

00:03:31.450 --> 00:03:34.300
Those people don't just
emerge out of nothing.

00:03:34.300 --> 00:03:36.160
They're created by
families, they're

00:03:36.160 --> 00:03:39.640
educated in schools, there's
all of these institutions that

00:03:39.640 --> 00:03:43.420
have to create that talented
labor pool for that employer,

00:03:43.420 --> 00:03:46.360
so that they can actually have
somebody whose wages they don't

00:03:46.360 --> 00:03:48.627
want to go too high to pay.

00:03:48.627 --> 00:03:50.460
They also have to think
about whether or not

00:03:50.460 --> 00:03:52.794
there's consumers for
whatever it is they're making.

00:03:52.794 --> 00:03:55.210
And part of what businesses
do is try to figure out things

00:03:55.210 --> 00:03:57.100
that people want to
buy, but they also

00:03:57.100 --> 00:03:58.700
need people who
actually have money,

00:03:58.700 --> 00:03:59.783
they can buy those things.

00:03:59.783 --> 00:04:03.490
They need to have that
consumer base available.

00:04:03.490 --> 00:04:06.040
And that we're talking
a lot these days

00:04:06.040 --> 00:04:09.940
about the role of
trade in consumption.

00:04:09.940 --> 00:04:11.902
So a one role a policy
has is whether or not

00:04:11.902 --> 00:04:14.110
we allow people from other
countries to buy our goods

00:04:14.110 --> 00:04:15.500
or whether or not
we import them.

00:04:15.500 --> 00:04:17.829
That's a policy question
around consumption.

00:04:17.829 --> 00:04:20.920
But it's also around the
well-being of families,

00:04:20.920 --> 00:04:23.230
because families comprise
the vast majority

00:04:23.230 --> 00:04:27.620
of end users of any of most
products produced in the United

00:04:27.620 --> 00:04:28.810
States.

00:04:28.810 --> 00:04:31.149
So, when you kind of step
back and look at this bigger

00:04:31.149 --> 00:04:33.565
picture, there's a lot of
things that firms don't control,

00:04:33.565 --> 00:04:35.470
but that are about
the institutions,

00:04:35.470 --> 00:04:39.040
and the supply of people, and
consumer demand that sit around

00:04:39.040 --> 00:04:40.290
what individual businesses do.

00:04:40.290 --> 00:04:41.831
So if you want to
understand actually

00:04:41.831 --> 00:04:43.390
what's good for the
economy, you have

00:04:43.390 --> 00:04:46.190
to take that larger picture.

00:04:46.190 --> 00:04:49.450
So in the book I talk about it.

00:04:49.450 --> 00:04:52.420
That we need to think of
both families and firms.

00:04:52.420 --> 00:04:55.420
And both of their
roles in the economy.

00:04:55.420 --> 00:04:58.630
And the book is called Finding
Time, a lot of what it's about

00:04:58.630 --> 00:05:02.290
is thinking about the conditions
under which people sell

00:05:02.290 --> 00:05:05.020
their time to employers, and
the conditions under which

00:05:05.020 --> 00:05:06.730
employers buy that time.

00:05:06.730 --> 00:05:09.825
How those two interact that
it's not just the business

00:05:09.825 --> 00:05:11.950
perspective, but that you
have to put both together

00:05:11.950 --> 00:05:15.280
to really understand
what's happening.

00:05:15.280 --> 00:05:17.440
DAVID BARRY: So if we,
up until this point,

00:05:17.440 --> 00:05:21.160
haven't really considered the
family aspect of the economy,

00:05:21.160 --> 00:05:25.300
it seems as though our picture,
or our understanding of how

00:05:25.300 --> 00:05:28.990
the economy actually
works, is pretty skewed.

00:05:28.990 --> 00:05:34.630
So what does this say about the
measures we're currently using

00:05:34.630 --> 00:05:38.290
to judge our economy's health?

00:05:38.290 --> 00:05:40.100
HEATHER BOUSHEY: That's
a great question.

00:05:40.100 --> 00:05:44.080
So there's two points I
want to focus on in that.

00:05:44.080 --> 00:05:45.310
One is that--

00:05:45.310 --> 00:05:47.560
One of the things I really
struggled in with the book,

00:05:47.560 --> 00:05:49.330
and struggled in,
in terms of thinking

00:05:49.330 --> 00:05:51.700
about how to advise
policymakers,

00:05:51.700 --> 00:05:53.846
is that when you
think about what

00:05:53.846 --> 00:05:55.720
we learn in economics,
what economic teaches,

00:05:55.720 --> 00:05:58.210
is so often the models,
I mean almost universally

00:05:58.210 --> 00:06:03.010
the models start by thinking
about an individual's actions.

00:06:03.010 --> 00:06:05.570
How is it that an individual
will act in the economy.

00:06:05.570 --> 00:06:07.840
And that's an important
place to start.

00:06:07.840 --> 00:06:09.640
But the reality
is, that most of us

00:06:09.640 --> 00:06:12.460
actually do the majority
of our consuming,

00:06:12.460 --> 00:06:15.100
and educating the
next generation,

00:06:15.100 --> 00:06:16.900
and even thinking
about labor supply,

00:06:16.900 --> 00:06:18.927
these decisions happen
inside families.

00:06:18.927 --> 00:06:21.510
And there's certainly economists
that have thought about that,

00:06:21.510 --> 00:06:24.580
but that sort of hasn't
infiltrated everything

00:06:24.580 --> 00:06:27.880
in terms of how we think about
what's good for the economy.

00:06:27.880 --> 00:06:32.980
So one, sort of starting place
for the question you asked

00:06:32.980 --> 00:06:36.900
is that thinking about not
just for the individual,

00:06:36.900 --> 00:06:39.640
but opening it up to really
think about the family

00:06:39.640 --> 00:06:44.110
side of the equation.

00:06:44.110 --> 00:06:46.540
To take a step back,
one of the things

00:06:46.540 --> 00:06:50.320
that we watch every
quarter is the nation's

00:06:50.320 --> 00:06:51.380
gross domestic product.

00:06:51.380 --> 00:06:51.880
Right?

00:06:51.880 --> 00:06:53.960
So that's the big
number that comes out.

00:06:53.960 --> 00:06:57.000
One of the most numbers in terms
of measuring our economy along

00:06:57.000 --> 00:06:59.159
with, I would argue,
the employment rate

00:06:59.159 --> 00:07:01.200
that comes out on the
first Friday of each month,

00:07:01.200 --> 00:07:03.630
and how our wages are doing,
and the income data that

00:07:03.630 --> 00:07:04.920
comes out once a year.

00:07:04.920 --> 00:07:06.750
But we watch this
GDP data and we

00:07:06.750 --> 00:07:08.710
think it means something
about our economy.

00:07:08.710 --> 00:07:09.210
Right?

00:07:09.210 --> 00:07:13.080
So we know now that the US
economy produced $18 trillion

00:07:13.080 --> 00:07:16.109
worth of goods and
services in 2016,

00:07:16.109 --> 00:07:18.150
which is the largest of
any country in the world,

00:07:18.150 --> 00:07:19.566
and is probably
actually therefore

00:07:19.566 --> 00:07:22.350
the largest of any
country in any world ever,

00:07:22.350 --> 00:07:25.360
right, because we're
growing over time.

00:07:25.360 --> 00:07:28.680
But one question that
that doesn't answer,

00:07:28.680 --> 00:07:31.410
that aggregate doesn't answer,
is, what does that actually

00:07:31.410 --> 00:07:32.730
look like across families.

00:07:32.730 --> 00:07:35.730
What does that actually
look like across America?

00:07:35.730 --> 00:07:38.640
And there are scholars who are
digging into this question,

00:07:38.640 --> 00:07:41.357
and sort of trying to understand
the connection between how

00:07:41.357 --> 00:07:43.440
well the economy is faring,
and what that actually

00:07:43.440 --> 00:07:47.160
looks like inside families
all across the United States.

00:07:47.160 --> 00:07:50.250
And they're finding
that if you look

00:07:50.250 --> 00:07:53.940
at economic growth
between 1980 and 2014,

00:07:53.940 --> 00:07:57.810
the US economy grew
by 61% for every adult

00:07:57.810 --> 00:07:59.010
in the United States.

00:07:59.010 --> 00:08:04.590
So 1980 to 2014, 61% per
adult. But when you actually

00:08:04.590 --> 00:08:07.110
match the data up
and look at what

00:08:07.110 --> 00:08:10.320
that looks like inside
families, what you find

00:08:10.320 --> 00:08:13.440
is that translates
into a 1% growth

00:08:13.440 --> 00:08:18.910
rate for all adults living in
families making less than--

00:08:18.910 --> 00:08:22.120
in the bottom 50% of
the income distribution.

00:08:22.120 --> 00:08:25.110
So the economy grew
by 61%, but families

00:08:25.110 --> 00:08:27.290
in the bottom half,
people in the bottom half

00:08:27.290 --> 00:08:29.970
saw a 1% gain over
that time period.

00:08:29.970 --> 00:08:32.070
While those at the top
saw these enormous gains.

00:08:32.070 --> 00:08:35.190
The top 1% saw
gains of about 204%.

00:08:35.190 --> 00:08:38.190
So when you open up and
you're not just thinking

00:08:38.190 --> 00:08:39.240
about the business case.

00:08:39.240 --> 00:08:43.380
You're not just thinking
about the traditional measures

00:08:43.380 --> 00:08:44.242
we use.

00:08:44.242 --> 00:08:46.200
You can get a deeper
understanding of what this

00:08:46.200 --> 00:08:47.930
looks like across families.

00:08:47.930 --> 00:08:52.590
That number on what growth
looks like across income

00:08:52.590 --> 00:08:54.090
distribution, is
very important when

00:08:54.090 --> 00:08:57.520
you think about what that
means for consumer demand.

00:08:57.520 --> 00:09:00.120
So the economy is growing, but
most people aren't actually

00:09:00.120 --> 00:09:01.050
gaining from growth.

00:09:01.050 --> 00:09:04.800
We can't expect them to be
increasing their consumption

00:09:04.800 --> 00:09:06.930
year after year after year
unless they are taking

00:09:06.930 --> 00:09:10.230
on more debt, which is something
I talk about, how that affects

00:09:10.230 --> 00:09:12.420
family economic security.

00:09:12.420 --> 00:09:15.300
It also has implications for
the capacity for families

00:09:15.300 --> 00:09:18.210
across the income
distribution, to be

00:09:18.210 --> 00:09:20.610
able to educate the
next generation,

00:09:20.610 --> 00:09:24.014
to be able to provide the
health and well-being and all

00:09:24.014 --> 00:09:25.680
that we need that is
actually supporting

00:09:25.680 --> 00:09:28.020
not only people, which
is certainly important,

00:09:28.020 --> 00:09:31.430
but supporting our
future labor supply.

00:09:31.430 --> 00:09:32.730
DAVID BARRY: Great, thank you.

00:09:32.730 --> 00:09:35.220
So yeah, so that leads kind
of to the next question which

00:09:35.220 --> 00:09:39.300
is, one thing you make
clear throughout the book,

00:09:39.300 --> 00:09:42.300
is that the economics
of work life conflict

00:09:42.300 --> 00:09:44.710
is not just a women's issue.

00:09:44.710 --> 00:09:47.400
It's not just an issue
for professional workers,

00:09:47.400 --> 00:09:51.510
or for low wage workers, really
it's an issue for everyone.

00:09:51.510 --> 00:09:53.704
What led you to that insight?

00:09:53.704 --> 00:09:55.620
And could you please
describe for the audience

00:09:55.620 --> 00:09:58.470
briefly how you
segmented your analysis.

00:09:58.470 --> 00:10:04.580
HEATHER BOUSHEY: Yeah, so
you know for a long time--

00:10:04.580 --> 00:10:05.930
I started out--

00:10:05.930 --> 00:10:08.580
I'm an economist and
I came to these issues

00:10:08.580 --> 00:10:11.850
because my primary research
interest is understanding

00:10:11.850 --> 00:10:15.360
the well-being of America's
families, economic well-being.

00:10:15.360 --> 00:10:17.850
And so that's what I've
studied and sort of thought

00:10:17.850 --> 00:10:20.640
about and over time one of
the most important trends

00:10:20.640 --> 00:10:24.116
that we've noticed since
the 1970s that has affected

00:10:24.116 --> 00:10:26.490
American families, is a movement
of women out of the home

00:10:26.490 --> 00:10:27.860
and into the labor force.

00:10:27.860 --> 00:10:29.670
It's had huge effects
on family income.

00:10:29.670 --> 00:10:31.597
It's affected the
time families had.

00:10:31.597 --> 00:10:32.930
So that was sort of my initial--

00:10:32.930 --> 00:10:35.415
it's like, oh wow, this
is the important thing.

00:10:35.415 --> 00:10:37.860
But when you think
about what that means,

00:10:37.860 --> 00:10:41.040
to have people change how
they spend their days,

00:10:41.040 --> 00:10:44.460
from spending it at home and to
spending it in the labor force,

00:10:44.460 --> 00:10:46.340
that isn't just something
that affects women.

00:10:46.340 --> 00:10:46.840
Right?

00:10:46.840 --> 00:10:49.590
Certainly they're the person of
taking that different action.

00:10:49.590 --> 00:10:50.090
Right?

00:10:50.090 --> 00:10:51.990
They're actually changing
what they're doing.

00:10:51.990 --> 00:10:54.360
But that actually then
affects everyone around them.

00:10:54.360 --> 00:10:56.190
It affects their partners.

00:10:56.190 --> 00:10:57.430
It affects their children.

00:10:57.430 --> 00:10:59.770
It affects their communities.

00:10:59.770 --> 00:11:02.970
It affects PTAs, League of
Women Voters, all the volunteer

00:11:02.970 --> 00:11:04.910
things that women used to do.

00:11:04.910 --> 00:11:06.480
So it affects
community institutions.

00:11:06.480 --> 00:11:10.030
And it also affects care for
the aging and the elderly.

00:11:10.030 --> 00:11:13.410
So all the different
activities that American women

00:11:13.410 --> 00:11:16.470
used to do when they were unem--

00:11:16.470 --> 00:11:20.490
not being paid in the
labor force, but at home.

00:11:20.490 --> 00:11:21.930
As they've shifted their time.

00:11:21.930 --> 00:11:23.580
It has these broader effects.

00:11:23.580 --> 00:11:27.810
So that's, in a nutshell, why
this isn't a women's issue.

00:11:27.810 --> 00:11:30.210
I mean it just so happens
that women are the people that

00:11:30.210 --> 00:11:31.180
change what they do.

00:11:31.180 --> 00:11:33.420
But it affects everyone.

00:11:33.420 --> 00:11:36.720
And understanding why they've
changed their employment

00:11:36.720 --> 00:11:38.850
patterns, and what that
means for men, and children

00:11:38.850 --> 00:11:40.266
and for families
and their income,

00:11:40.266 --> 00:11:43.560
is really the focus of the book.

00:11:43.560 --> 00:11:47.010
I look at families.

00:11:47.010 --> 00:11:48.480
I divide them into three groups.

00:11:48.480 --> 00:11:50.130
I look at low income
families, families

00:11:50.130 --> 00:11:52.950
in the bottom 30% of
the income distribution,

00:11:52.950 --> 00:11:54.980
professional families
which I define as families

00:11:54.980 --> 00:11:57.770
in the top 20%, where at
least one person has a college

00:11:57.770 --> 00:11:58.640
degree.

00:11:58.640 --> 00:12:02.180
So it's sort of
taking out families

00:12:02.180 --> 00:12:05.060
that may be high
incomes but maybe

00:12:05.060 --> 00:12:09.380
sort of either a self-made
or just a different kind

00:12:09.380 --> 00:12:11.390
of professional experience.

00:12:11.390 --> 00:12:13.820
And then the middle is
sort of the middle 50%.

00:12:13.820 --> 00:12:17.644
So I talk about
what the economics

00:12:17.644 --> 00:12:18.560
are of those families.

00:12:18.560 --> 00:12:20.430
How they've shifted over time.

00:12:20.430 --> 00:12:24.519
And then look at them as
three different groups.

00:12:24.519 --> 00:12:25.310
DAVID BARRY: Great.

00:12:25.310 --> 00:12:30.560
So I wanted to drill down a
little on each of the groups.

00:12:30.560 --> 00:12:33.500
So first, take for instance,
the group at the top.

00:12:33.500 --> 00:12:35.540
So what you call the
professional class,

00:12:35.540 --> 00:12:38.780
that is soaring above
and sounding the alarm.

00:12:38.780 --> 00:12:41.630
You, and I, and many
of us at Google,

00:12:41.630 --> 00:12:43.310
are probably in
this category trying

00:12:43.310 --> 00:12:46.760
to juggle work, family,
friends, and wondering

00:12:46.760 --> 00:12:49.260
where fun fits in.

00:12:49.260 --> 00:12:51.890
But that's not really the
whole story for this group.

00:12:51.890 --> 00:12:53.960
Could you please describe
why the situation

00:12:53.960 --> 00:12:57.890
for this group at the top,
indicates a larger problem?

00:12:57.890 --> 00:13:03.182
HEATHER BOUSHEY:
Yeah, so yes I can.

00:13:03.182 --> 00:13:05.390
So I also want to explain
the metaphor about soaring,

00:13:05.390 --> 00:13:07.098
but I'm going to get
to that in a minute.

00:13:07.098 --> 00:13:09.410
So just ping that and we'll
come back to that one.

00:13:09.410 --> 00:13:12.110
So when you look at what's
changed for families over time

00:13:12.110 --> 00:13:15.014
and this transformation of
how women spend their days.

00:13:15.014 --> 00:13:17.180
What you see is, of course,
in professional families

00:13:17.180 --> 00:13:20.780
and I'm guessing
many of us in here

00:13:20.780 --> 00:13:23.960
have a sense of this, is that
families at the top typically

00:13:23.960 --> 00:13:27.620
now have both men and
women in the workplace,

00:13:27.620 --> 00:13:29.090
and no one at home full time.

00:13:29.090 --> 00:13:33.290
So they have these two incomes
but still no one at home

00:13:33.290 --> 00:13:35.750
to provide all the things
that families need.

00:13:35.750 --> 00:13:37.901
You know, care for
children, the elderly,

00:13:37.901 --> 00:13:40.400
waiting home for the cable guy,
whatever it is that families

00:13:40.400 --> 00:13:41.990
need somebody to do.

00:13:41.990 --> 00:13:47.070
And we hear a lot about
these families in the media,

00:13:47.070 --> 00:13:50.180
more so than I think the middle
and the low income families,

00:13:50.180 --> 00:13:52.580
because that way of living
can be incredibly stressful.

00:13:52.580 --> 00:13:55.940
Our world isn't really set
up to have no one at home.

00:13:55.940 --> 00:14:00.650
And so we hear a lot in,
especially on the style pages,

00:14:00.650 --> 00:14:03.380
or in not necessarily always
on the business pages which

00:14:03.380 --> 00:14:04.940
is where I think
it should often be,

00:14:04.940 --> 00:14:07.370
but we hear about the
struggles that families face.

00:14:07.370 --> 00:14:11.180
And fundamentally, it's that
there's a squeeze on time.

00:14:11.180 --> 00:14:13.640
And so I think once you sort
of think about it that way,

00:14:13.640 --> 00:14:16.340
and you start sort of
watching this conversation

00:14:16.340 --> 00:14:17.690
that we're having as a country.

00:14:17.690 --> 00:14:19.970
So much of it is that
families are really

00:14:19.970 --> 00:14:22.430
stressed out because they're
squeezed for time, even

00:14:22.430 --> 00:14:24.050
at the top.

00:14:24.050 --> 00:14:26.160
Because money can
purchase some things.

00:14:26.160 --> 00:14:27.620
It can purchase prepared meals.

00:14:27.620 --> 00:14:29.240
It can purchase childcare.

00:14:29.240 --> 00:14:32.870
But what it can't purchase,
is that family meal together.

00:14:32.870 --> 00:14:33.370
Right?

00:14:33.370 --> 00:14:34.700
If you actually
want to spend time

00:14:34.700 --> 00:14:36.741
with your children, or
your spouse, or your loved

00:14:36.741 --> 00:14:39.350
one, or your ailing mom,
like you actually still need

00:14:39.350 --> 00:14:40.340
that time to do that.

00:14:40.340 --> 00:14:43.400
And how to juggle that, when
you have two careers that

00:14:43.400 --> 00:14:46.389
often take up very long hours.

00:14:46.389 --> 00:14:47.930
So I talk a lot in
the book about how

00:14:47.930 --> 00:14:54.290
we need to recognize what
long hours do to families,

00:14:54.290 --> 00:14:58.010
and what the lack of access
to paid time off, paid family

00:14:58.010 --> 00:15:01.970
leave, paid both parental
and family caregiving

00:15:01.970 --> 00:15:05.740
leave, and access to high
quality affordable care means.

00:15:05.740 --> 00:15:07.910
And that even for
families at the top who

00:15:07.910 --> 00:15:12.050
can afford to outsource child
care, elder care whatever it is

00:15:12.050 --> 00:15:14.960
that they need, there's
still that stress and anxiety

00:15:14.960 --> 00:15:16.890
around it.

00:15:16.890 --> 00:15:17.390
Yeah.

00:15:17.390 --> 00:15:19.370
DAVID BARRY: Sure.

00:15:19.370 --> 00:15:20.040
So then yeah.

00:15:20.040 --> 00:15:23.000
Like take a look at the
lower end of the spectrum

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:26.820
now, the stuck low
income families.

00:15:26.820 --> 00:15:29.960
So this group has
struggled for some time.

00:15:29.960 --> 00:15:34.490
Have you noticed that something
has changed for this group?

00:15:34.490 --> 00:15:36.860
And compared to the
group at the top,

00:15:36.860 --> 00:15:39.810
is there something that's not
getting enough attention here?

00:15:39.810 --> 00:15:40.922
HEATHER BOUSHEY: Yeah.

00:15:40.922 --> 00:15:42.380
Well, in the book
I try to actually

00:15:42.380 --> 00:15:44.559
lay out some parallels
between how we think

00:15:44.559 --> 00:15:46.850
about the challenges for
professional families, and how

00:15:46.850 --> 00:15:47.570
that also--

00:15:47.570 --> 00:15:49.892
how you see similar challenges
for low income families.

00:15:49.892 --> 00:15:51.350
Of course, they
look very different

00:15:51.350 --> 00:15:54.350
because of resource constraints,
in low income families.

00:15:54.350 --> 00:15:57.890
But one commonality is that
low income families also

00:15:57.890 --> 00:16:00.920
don't have a full time
stay at home caregiver.

00:16:00.920 --> 00:16:02.850
Just like families at the top.

00:16:02.850 --> 00:16:05.540
But they're doing it
typically with one--

00:16:05.540 --> 00:16:09.509
disproportionately they have
one caregiver, one parent.

00:16:09.509 --> 00:16:10.800
If it's a family with children.

00:16:10.800 --> 00:16:13.520
So they have one parent
and that parent also works.

00:16:13.520 --> 00:16:16.610
So they also were struggling
with the time constraints,

00:16:16.610 --> 00:16:18.350
that families at the
top are, but they're

00:16:18.350 --> 00:16:20.420
doing it on one
earnings, you know,

00:16:20.420 --> 00:16:22.700
rather than two, which
families at the top have.

00:16:22.700 --> 00:16:24.830
So that's sort of one
commonality, where

00:16:24.830 --> 00:16:28.040
I think we could be thinking
about the challenges

00:16:28.040 --> 00:16:30.530
that low income families
face, and how that--

00:16:30.530 --> 00:16:33.610
other solutions that might
hit both kinds of families.

00:16:33.610 --> 00:16:35.985
Is sort of one of the things
that I'm always looking for.

00:16:35.985 --> 00:16:38.737
How can we actually get
to some sort of action.

00:16:38.737 --> 00:16:40.820
So one of the things that's
changed for low income

00:16:40.820 --> 00:16:44.210
families, of course, over
the past half century,

00:16:44.210 --> 00:16:51.360
has been this movement away
from stable family structures.

00:16:51.360 --> 00:16:55.190
So it used to be that
the probability of having

00:16:55.190 --> 00:16:57.140
two parents and a
stay at home mom

00:16:57.140 --> 00:17:00.150
was much more similar
across families top, middle,

00:17:00.150 --> 00:17:01.460
and bottom.

00:17:01.460 --> 00:17:04.700
Certainly when we laid out
the basics of our nation's

00:17:04.700 --> 00:17:07.619
social insurance and labor
protections in the 1930s,

00:17:07.619 --> 00:17:09.410
It was a case that the
majority of families

00:17:09.410 --> 00:17:12.050
looked like that, sort of
that traditional family,

00:17:12.050 --> 00:17:14.227
even if they were
low income families.

00:17:14.227 --> 00:17:16.310
And one of the things
that's been well documented,

00:17:16.310 --> 00:17:18.750
is that alongside
rising inequality,

00:17:18.750 --> 00:17:22.910
you've seen this rising
disparity in family structure.

00:17:22.910 --> 00:17:24.859
And so families at the
bottom, increasingly

00:17:24.859 --> 00:17:26.599
have unstable families.

00:17:26.599 --> 00:17:28.910
Families that are mixed,
divorce, remarriage,

00:17:28.910 --> 00:17:30.600
and the like.

00:17:30.600 --> 00:17:36.350
And that is both chaotic, but
too often leaves families still

00:17:36.350 --> 00:17:38.200
with no one at home
to provide care,

00:17:38.200 --> 00:17:40.070
but still having
insufficient income.

00:17:40.070 --> 00:17:41.760
So that's one big change.

00:17:41.760 --> 00:17:46.227
The second of course, is
that jobs are changing.

00:17:46.227 --> 00:17:47.810
And what you've been
seeing especially

00:17:47.810 --> 00:17:49.730
among low income
families, is an increase

00:17:49.730 --> 00:17:52.830
in scheduling unpredictability.

00:17:52.830 --> 00:17:56.600
So alongside the fact that
incomes for low income families

00:17:56.600 --> 00:17:59.990
pretty much haven't
grown since 1979,

00:17:59.990 --> 00:18:04.610
you've seen this increase in
scheduling unpredictability.

00:18:04.610 --> 00:18:06.176
Which makes it
hard to figure out

00:18:06.176 --> 00:18:07.550
how you're going
to go to school,

00:18:07.550 --> 00:18:10.190
or juggle childcare, any of
the things that you need to do,

00:18:10.190 --> 00:18:12.398
if you actually don't know
what your schedule is more

00:18:12.398 --> 00:18:14.090
than a few days in advance.

00:18:14.090 --> 00:18:16.894
So that's one thing, and
then third, of course,

00:18:16.894 --> 00:18:18.560
is the lack of income
growth that you've

00:18:18.560 --> 00:18:23.300
seen for families at the bottom,
even though they have they

00:18:23.300 --> 00:18:25.190
typically have this earner.

00:18:25.190 --> 00:18:28.400
And in fact, for
low income families,

00:18:28.400 --> 00:18:31.460
if you hadn't had that
increase in women's labor force

00:18:31.460 --> 00:18:35.180
participation rates, and
the added wages of women,

00:18:35.180 --> 00:18:38.000
family income would have fallen
much further than it actually

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:40.880
did between 1979 and 2014.

00:18:40.880 --> 00:18:44.010
DAVID BARRY: Your last
group is the middle class.

00:18:44.010 --> 00:18:48.800
You used stalled middle class
the way that you describe it.

00:18:48.800 --> 00:18:52.310
What struck you most about this
group when you looked at them?

00:18:52.310 --> 00:18:55.410
HEATHER BOUSHEY: Well,
it's the biggest group.

00:18:55.410 --> 00:19:00.140
In the-- and this is sort of
the sword stuck and stalled

00:19:00.140 --> 00:19:01.760
kind of metaphor.

00:19:01.760 --> 00:19:03.890
In the book, I talk
about the middle class.

00:19:03.890 --> 00:19:05.940
And I'm from Washington state.

00:19:05.940 --> 00:19:07.460
I grew up near Seattle.

00:19:07.460 --> 00:19:11.660
And in 1980-- and a lot of my
data started in 1979 so about

00:19:11.660 --> 00:19:13.070
the same time--

00:19:13.070 --> 00:19:14.600
Mount St. Helens blew up.

00:19:14.600 --> 00:19:18.300
And that's a fact, we all
know that that's true.

00:19:18.300 --> 00:19:22.652
But as an economist, one of
the most important charts

00:19:22.652 --> 00:19:24.110
that you look at
if you're thinking

00:19:24.110 --> 00:19:25.651
about the well-being
of family income

00:19:25.651 --> 00:19:28.830
is this rise in family
income over time.

00:19:28.830 --> 00:19:32.660
And if you look at it
between 1947 and 1979,

00:19:32.660 --> 00:19:36.020
you see this straight up
increase in family income.

00:19:36.020 --> 00:19:38.930
Just kind of like rising up at a
45 degree, it's not 45 degrees,

00:19:38.930 --> 00:19:41.600
but rising up pretty
sharply, very nicely.

00:19:41.600 --> 00:19:44.240
Kind of like moving up the
side of a beautiful mountain.

00:19:44.240 --> 00:19:45.170
Right?

00:19:45.170 --> 00:19:48.595
And then after 1980,
the chart changes.

00:19:48.595 --> 00:19:51.699
So instead of going up, it sort
of kind of has this flatness,

00:19:51.699 --> 00:19:53.240
and it's kind of a
little bit craggy.

00:19:53.240 --> 00:19:55.230
And basically, every time
I look at that chart,

00:19:55.230 --> 00:19:56.780
I think of Mount St.
Helens blowing up.

00:19:56.780 --> 00:19:59.000
It looks like the top is
just blown, been blown right

00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:01.830
off America's middle class.

00:20:01.830 --> 00:20:06.200
And so that's what I think
is basically happened.

00:20:06.200 --> 00:20:09.110
And one thing I talk about in
the book was an analysis that I

00:20:09.110 --> 00:20:14.360
did, is that were it not for the
increase in women's labor force

00:20:14.360 --> 00:20:17.540
participation and the
increasing women's earnings,

00:20:17.540 --> 00:20:19.610
that family income which
for the middle class

00:20:19.610 --> 00:20:23.930
has grown by about 12% between
1979 and 2013 or 2014--

00:20:23.930 --> 00:20:26.270
I can't remember actually
what year the data stops--

00:20:26.270 --> 00:20:30.590
but about then, about 12%.

00:20:30.590 --> 00:20:36.050
Had it not been for the added
hours and earnings of women,

00:20:36.050 --> 00:20:39.110
that small increase that
middle class families saw

00:20:39.110 --> 00:20:41.510
would have actually
been a decline.

00:20:41.510 --> 00:20:44.930
So it's only because of the
added labor force participation

00:20:44.930 --> 00:20:47.480
of women, that you actually
see any increase at all

00:20:47.480 --> 00:20:50.540
in middle class
incomes, since 1979.

00:20:50.540 --> 00:20:52.487
So those families,
just like families

00:20:52.487 --> 00:20:55.070
at the top and the bottom, are
struggling with the same issues

00:20:55.070 --> 00:20:56.420
with the lack of time.

00:20:56.420 --> 00:20:57.470
Women are working more.

00:20:57.470 --> 00:20:59.900
Families don't have that full
time stay at home caregiver

00:20:59.900 --> 00:21:00.890
anymore.

00:21:00.890 --> 00:21:04.490
But the world has not
really adapted to this.

00:21:04.490 --> 00:21:08.180
So crazily, we live in a
country where schools still

00:21:08.180 --> 00:21:10.670
shut down for months at
a time, leaving families

00:21:10.670 --> 00:21:13.896
having to negotiate summer care
and all these sorts of things,

00:21:13.896 --> 00:21:16.520
even though you don't have-- we
don't sort of live in a farming

00:21:16.520 --> 00:21:19.220
community, more where
that makes a lot of sense.

00:21:19.220 --> 00:21:21.470
But that's just sort of one
kind of tip of the iceberg

00:21:21.470 --> 00:21:23.660
example of all the ways that--

00:21:23.660 --> 00:21:26.505
the fact that families
need the income of women,

00:21:26.505 --> 00:21:28.130
at the top, the
middle, and the bottom.

00:21:28.130 --> 00:21:31.580
That they're struggling
with this lack of time.

00:21:31.580 --> 00:21:35.210
That we haven't really
integrated into our thinking,

00:21:35.210 --> 00:21:37.406
well how do we help
families cope with this.

00:21:37.406 --> 00:21:39.030
And then of course
throughout the book,

00:21:39.030 --> 00:21:42.740
I talk about well, there
are economic implications

00:21:42.740 --> 00:21:44.460
of not addressing this.

00:21:44.460 --> 00:21:44.960
Right?

00:21:44.960 --> 00:21:47.750
Because even though
families are working more,

00:21:47.750 --> 00:21:52.490
they're doing so in a way that
they're really struggling.

00:21:52.490 --> 00:21:54.840
And there are potential
downsides to the economy,

00:21:54.840 --> 00:21:58.050
the lack of income growth
affects consumption and demand,

00:21:58.050 --> 00:21:59.730
and the way that
we're failing to think

00:21:59.730 --> 00:22:03.000
about the full gamut
of labor supply issues

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:06.060
means that we are actually
suppressing labor supply more

00:22:06.060 --> 00:22:10.800
than we need to be, both
now and really risking

00:22:10.800 --> 00:22:13.310
the next generation.

00:22:13.310 --> 00:22:15.180
DAVID BARRY: Great, thank you.

