to have implemented statewide
paid parental and family

00:23:55.590 --> 00:23:59.370
leave, on top of a long standing
individual disability insurance

00:23:59.370 --> 00:23:59.920
program.

00:23:59.920 --> 00:24:02.700
There are now four states that
have paid family medical leave.

00:24:02.700 --> 00:24:04.410
District of Columbia
has just passed it

00:24:04.410 --> 00:24:06.240
and now we have to wait,
because we are not a state,

00:24:06.240 --> 00:24:07.980
we have to wait for Congress
to determine whether or not

00:24:07.980 --> 00:24:09.870
we can actually go
forward with the law

00:24:09.870 --> 00:24:11.800
that we democratically passed.

00:24:11.800 --> 00:24:16.162
But that's a different
lecture on states' rights.

00:24:16.162 --> 00:24:18.120
And so there are places
that are moving forward

00:24:18.120 --> 00:24:19.745
on paid family medical
leave, and there

00:24:19.745 --> 00:24:23.400
are dozens of places that have
implemented paid sick days.

00:24:23.400 --> 00:24:26.010
I know you all here at Google
have access to paid sick days,

00:24:26.010 --> 00:24:27.426
when you get sick
and have the flu

00:24:27.426 --> 00:24:30.084
and you can't come into
work, but the majority of,

00:24:30.084 --> 00:24:32.250
especially of low wage
workers in the United States,

00:24:32.250 --> 00:24:36.130
do not have access to
any paid time off at all,

00:24:36.130 --> 00:24:38.730
let alone the right to stay
home when they have the flu.

00:24:38.730 --> 00:24:40.110
So that's the
first area, and one

00:24:40.110 --> 00:24:42.810
where we've seen a lot of
really exciting movement

00:24:42.810 --> 00:24:44.160
at the state and local level.

00:24:44.160 --> 00:24:47.430
And in fact in
November, two states

00:24:47.430 --> 00:24:49.840
move forward on paid sick
days for their states,

00:24:49.840 --> 00:24:52.500
requiring that employers provide
five to seven days of paid

00:24:52.500 --> 00:24:54.480
sick days.

00:24:54.480 --> 00:24:56.070
The second, is that
we need policies

00:24:56.070 --> 00:24:59.430
for when we need to be
there at work, not at home.

00:24:59.430 --> 00:25:01.650
And to make that
work for families--

00:25:01.650 --> 00:25:03.450
and here in that
bucket I put things

00:25:03.450 --> 00:25:07.860
like predictable
scheduling, making sure

00:25:07.860 --> 00:25:11.640
that we have adequate overtime
protections, and protections

00:25:11.640 --> 00:25:14.280
for part time workers,
and also the right

00:25:14.280 --> 00:25:16.180
to request flexibility.

00:25:16.180 --> 00:25:20.340
So in the United States
today, less than one

00:25:20.340 --> 00:25:23.010
in ten, far less than one in
ten private sector workers

00:25:23.010 --> 00:25:24.810
are represented by a union.

00:25:24.810 --> 00:25:26.370
And millions of
people don't even

00:25:26.370 --> 00:25:28.650
have the right to ask
their employer if they want

00:25:28.650 --> 00:25:30.221
to have a flexible schedule.

00:25:30.221 --> 00:25:32.220
And millions of people
don't know their schedule

00:25:32.220 --> 00:25:34.140
more than a few days in advance.

00:25:34.140 --> 00:25:36.685
Now I often don't know my
schedule more than a few days

00:25:36.685 --> 00:25:39.060
in advance, so this also
happens to professional workers,

00:25:39.060 --> 00:25:42.102
but we're paid a lot more money
than folks that work in retail

00:25:42.102 --> 00:25:43.560
or in food service
you have to deal

00:25:43.560 --> 00:25:45.143
with unpredictable
schedules, but have

00:25:45.143 --> 00:25:47.650
to do it on a lot less income.

00:25:47.650 --> 00:25:50.700
So these are places where
the legislation that we

00:25:50.700 --> 00:25:53.310
have at the federal level,
the Fair Labor Standards Act,

00:25:53.310 --> 00:25:54.810
it says nothing
about these issues.

00:25:54.810 --> 00:25:56.130
I mean it says something
about overtime,

00:25:56.130 --> 00:25:57.880
but it doesn't say
anything about overtime

00:25:57.880 --> 00:25:59.940
for people that
are not production

00:25:59.940 --> 00:26:02.550
workers, or salaried
workers, that you know,

00:26:02.550 --> 00:26:06.240
which is a lot of us that
have no protections at all.

00:26:06.240 --> 00:26:09.930
So we need to rethink what does
the economy look like today,

00:26:09.930 --> 00:26:12.780
and how can we support families.

00:26:12.780 --> 00:26:15.240
We need policies
around care, that

00:26:15.240 --> 00:26:19.800
provide safe, affordable,
and enriching options

00:26:19.800 --> 00:26:22.110
for care for children,
but also increasingly

00:26:22.110 --> 00:26:24.510
the aging of the elderly.

00:26:24.510 --> 00:26:29.790
There are very few
options for people

00:26:29.790 --> 00:26:32.850
barring selling down
all of your assets

00:26:32.850 --> 00:26:36.120
when you get older, to
provide some of the services

00:26:36.120 --> 00:26:38.854
that many older folks need,
so that they can age in place.

00:26:38.854 --> 00:26:41.520
And we haven't spent enough time
as a nation really figuring out

00:26:41.520 --> 00:26:43.500
actually how to
address that, let alone

00:26:43.500 --> 00:26:46.260
making sure that folks
have access to health care.

00:26:46.260 --> 00:26:48.200
And then finally,
the fourth bucket

00:26:48.200 --> 00:26:49.590
is issues around fairness.

00:26:49.590 --> 00:26:52.695
Really making sure that as
we think about this basket,

00:26:52.695 --> 00:26:55.070
making sure that these policies
are available to both men

00:26:55.070 --> 00:26:55.750
and women.

00:26:55.750 --> 00:26:58.950
That we're not discriminating
along the lines of gender

00:26:58.950 --> 00:27:02.450
or anything else, because it's
the case that in a world where

00:27:02.450 --> 00:27:05.000
most women are in
the workplace, that

00:27:05.000 --> 00:27:07.850
means almost every employee
at some point in time

00:27:07.850 --> 00:27:10.850
will have some reason that they
need flexibility or time off,

00:27:10.850 --> 00:27:11.720
to provide care.

00:27:11.720 --> 00:27:15.710
Be it for a child, or for a
friend, or for an aging parent.

00:27:15.710 --> 00:27:20.180
And it's really important
to remember that for men,

00:27:20.180 --> 00:27:23.090
not only is it really
important that they're there

00:27:23.090 --> 00:27:25.430
in the early days of
having a new child.

00:27:25.430 --> 00:27:28.217
Be it that through adoption
or becoming a new parent,

00:27:28.217 --> 00:27:30.800
that there's a lot of evidence
just how important that time is

00:27:30.800 --> 00:27:33.090
not just for moms but for dads.

00:27:33.090 --> 00:27:37.820
But it used to be that if
a man's mom or dad fell

00:27:37.820 --> 00:27:40.710
ill and somebody needed
to take care of her,

00:27:40.710 --> 00:27:42.680
he had a stay at home
wife that could do that.

00:27:42.680 --> 00:27:45.230
And of course now that's not
the case in most families.

00:27:45.230 --> 00:27:47.240
And so both men and
women are having

00:27:47.240 --> 00:27:50.540
to deal with needing
the flexibility to care

00:27:50.540 --> 00:27:51.770
for an aging population.

00:27:51.770 --> 00:27:55.730
And so really making
sure that we're not--

00:27:55.730 --> 00:27:58.280
that we're recognizing that
this is a universal problem, not

00:27:58.280 --> 00:28:01.640
just a problem for some people,
when they have new children

00:28:01.640 --> 00:28:04.620
is really an important
piece of the puzzle.

00:28:04.620 --> 00:28:07.430
So, a little bit
on state and local.

00:28:07.430 --> 00:28:10.190
So as I said, there's been some
great work around family leave

00:28:10.190 --> 00:28:12.059
and paid sick days.

00:28:12.059 --> 00:28:13.850
You know California
has also been a leader.

00:28:13.850 --> 00:28:17.000
San Francisco has been a
leader, especially in issues

00:28:17.000 --> 00:28:18.250
around predictable scheduling.

00:28:18.250 --> 00:28:20.150
So there's some
legislation that's

00:28:20.150 --> 00:28:22.640
now in place in San
Francisco, around that

00:28:22.640 --> 00:28:24.890
and a number of other
places in the country that

00:28:24.890 --> 00:28:28.430
requires employers to give
notice on what an employee

00:28:28.430 --> 00:28:29.480
schedule is.

00:28:29.480 --> 00:28:31.280
There's also a lot
of economic evidence

00:28:31.280 --> 00:28:32.990
that policies like
that are actually not

00:28:32.990 --> 00:28:37.260
just good for the employee, but
they're also good for business.

00:28:37.260 --> 00:28:39.770
So in much of the book as I
talk about this policy agenda,

00:28:39.770 --> 00:28:43.250
I spent a lot of time digging
through the economic evidence,

00:28:43.250 --> 00:28:46.850
to show that these policies
can improve labor supply, they

00:28:46.850 --> 00:28:50.210
reduce employee turnover,
they increase retention,

00:28:50.210 --> 00:28:52.110
they can stabilize demand.

00:28:52.110 --> 00:28:55.920
That all of this is a
part of this conversation.

00:28:55.920 --> 00:28:57.860
So it's not just
about the family piece

00:28:57.860 --> 00:29:00.440
and how this is a nice
thing to do for people,

00:29:00.440 --> 00:29:03.230
but that this basket
of policies, there

00:29:03.230 --> 00:29:05.210
is just reams of
economic evidence

00:29:05.210 --> 00:29:08.000
that would fill this
room, that makes the case,

00:29:08.000 --> 00:29:10.512
that there are strong
economic benefits to doing so.

00:29:10.512 --> 00:29:11.970
