escalation of consumption,

00:35:40.190 --> 00:35:43.810
that for the vast majority
of American families,

00:35:43.810 --> 00:35:45.370
I think they are
probably rightfully

00:35:45.370 --> 00:35:47.770
frustrated that
somebody is getting

00:35:47.770 --> 00:35:49.540
the money from the
gains at growth

00:35:49.540 --> 00:35:51.430
and it certainly is not them.

00:35:51.430 --> 00:35:54.040
And so, how much are
people using debt

00:35:54.040 --> 00:35:55.180
as a way to compensate?

00:35:55.180 --> 00:35:58.450
Like oh, I'm sure I'll get
that pay out next year.

00:35:58.450 --> 00:36:01.010
I don't know and I
can't speak to that.

00:36:01.010 --> 00:36:03.730
But I do think that
these are twin problems.

00:36:03.730 --> 00:36:09.580
And one certainly that it would
be good to keep talking about

00:36:09.580 --> 00:36:12.010
AUDIENCE: Question
on the policy on pay

00:36:12.010 --> 00:36:14.680
for care and other things.

00:36:14.680 --> 00:36:18.190
How do you prevent people
from abusing the system?

00:36:18.190 --> 00:36:20.070
HEATHER BOUSHEY: For
like paid family leave?

00:36:20.070 --> 00:36:20.970
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:36:20.970 --> 00:36:23.053
HEATHER BOUSHEY: Yeah, so
that's a great question.

00:36:24.710 --> 00:36:28.210
So first off, what you
have here in California

00:36:28.210 --> 00:36:31.210
is this longstanding temporary
disability insurance program

00:36:31.210 --> 00:36:34.280
and there is a agency
that administers that

00:36:34.280 --> 00:36:36.640
and you know ensures that if
somebody says that they're

00:36:36.640 --> 00:36:39.040
sick, it has to be verified.

00:36:39.040 --> 00:36:41.660
So there's rules in
place to verify it.

00:36:41.660 --> 00:36:45.580
And when you add the paid
family and parental leave,

00:36:45.580 --> 00:36:47.800
I mean it's super easy
to verify whether or not

00:36:47.800 --> 00:36:50.980
somebody has a child, has a new
child coming into their family

00:36:50.980 --> 00:36:52.992
through adoption or birth.

00:36:52.992 --> 00:36:55.500
But for the care, like
care for the elderly,

00:36:55.500 --> 00:36:57.510
or care for someone
who is seriously ill,

00:36:57.510 --> 00:37:02.076
it can be a little bit more
difficult to verify that.

00:37:02.076 --> 00:37:03.450
The federal law
that we have that

00:37:03.450 --> 00:37:05.970
provides unpaid leave, which
is the Family and Medical Leave

00:37:05.970 --> 00:37:11.005
Act, has a verification
process in it.

00:37:11.005 --> 00:37:13.410
And the way that they do
it, is that your employer

00:37:13.410 --> 00:37:15.970
is because you are
absent from work,

00:37:15.970 --> 00:37:19.034
so the employer is the one that
knows that you're not there.

00:37:19.034 --> 00:37:21.450
The employer has the right to
ask you for a doctor's note,

00:37:21.450 --> 00:37:22.680
ask for some verification.

00:37:22.680 --> 00:37:27.600
They don't have to, but they
have the right to do that,

00:37:27.600 --> 00:37:28.470
to insure.

00:37:28.470 --> 00:37:34.360
So if we moved to a federal
paid family leave, family

00:37:34.360 --> 00:37:37.080
medical leave
program, we can learn

00:37:37.080 --> 00:37:40.099
from what's happened in the
States that already do that.

00:37:40.099 --> 00:37:41.640
So we could learn
from what, you know

00:37:41.640 --> 00:37:44.730
how they make sure that people
comply here in California,

00:37:44.730 --> 00:37:47.200
and in the other states
that have that program.

00:37:47.200 --> 00:37:49.140
New Jersey, New York,
and Rhode Island.

00:37:49.140 --> 00:37:51.223
And we can learn from what
we know from the Family

00:37:51.223 --> 00:37:53.130
and Medical Leave Act.

00:37:53.130 --> 00:37:56.520
I will say also, there's
a lot of incentive

00:37:56.520 --> 00:37:58.920
on the part of
employees to not lie

00:37:58.920 --> 00:38:01.740
to their employer
about important things.

00:38:01.740 --> 00:38:04.710
Again, the vast majority-- the
share of private sector workers

00:38:04.710 --> 00:38:07.470
that are represented by a
union that have job protection,

00:38:07.470 --> 00:38:08.890
is 7%.

00:38:08.890 --> 00:38:11.400
So the vast majority
of American workers

00:38:11.400 --> 00:38:14.310
don't have the right
to keep their job.

00:38:14.310 --> 00:38:16.920
And while they may get
the right to this benefit,

00:38:16.920 --> 00:38:19.190
employers certainly
have a lot of leeway.

00:38:19.190 --> 00:38:22.770
Somebody is going to lie to you
about this is probably not--

00:38:22.770 --> 00:38:24.450
there may be other
performance issues,

00:38:24.450 --> 00:38:26.820
so I actually have a high
degree of confidence,

00:38:26.820 --> 00:38:28.740
that the research
that we've seen

00:38:28.740 --> 00:38:33.330
that shows that there isn't
a great degree of lying about

00:38:33.330 --> 00:38:35.610
the-- around issues
like around leave,

00:38:35.610 --> 00:38:38.430
is because most people are
honest with their employers,

00:38:38.430 --> 00:38:40.680
because they know that if
they aren't a good employee,

00:38:40.680 --> 00:38:42.280
that they can lose their job.

00:38:42.280 --> 00:38:45.540
So I think that, in and of
itself, is probably the best--

00:38:45.540 --> 00:38:48.690
we already have this really
great defense against people

00:38:48.690 --> 00:38:51.460
abusing the system.

00:38:51.460 --> 00:38:54.090
AUDIENCE: I know the
universal basic income

00:38:54.090 --> 00:38:57.600
is a big thing globally
and potentially locally

00:38:57.600 --> 00:39:02.760
as well, I mean does that change
the equation of the groups

00:39:02.760 --> 00:39:05.360
or any of these circumstances?

00:39:05.360 --> 00:39:07.060
HEATHER BOUSHEY:
It's a good question.

00:39:07.060 --> 00:39:08.790
I always hear a lot about
universal basic income

00:39:08.790 --> 00:39:09.730
when I'm in California.

00:39:09.730 --> 00:39:10.688
It's fun to talk about.

00:39:13.064 --> 00:39:14.730
So it depends, I mean
so I think there's

00:39:14.730 --> 00:39:15.840
a lot of different
ideas, like when

00:39:15.840 --> 00:39:17.370
you say that it's like
one of these tests.

00:39:17.370 --> 00:39:19.260
What do you mean when
you say that, right?

00:39:19.260 --> 00:39:24.140
So one vision is that we
would give every American

00:39:24.140 --> 00:39:26.580
a check for some amount of
money and so it wouldn't really

00:39:26.580 --> 00:39:28.290
be really we're
placing any benefits,

00:39:28.290 --> 00:39:31.420
it would just be some sort
of dividend for everyone.

00:39:31.420 --> 00:39:33.000
Another vision
and it's certainly

00:39:33.000 --> 00:39:37.200
what the United States thought
about, the Nixon's family

00:39:37.200 --> 00:39:39.100
assistance program
from the 1970s,

00:39:39.100 --> 00:39:40.980
which was a basic
income guarantee,

00:39:40.980 --> 00:39:46.350
was a way of really providing
a basic income so that everyone

00:39:46.350 --> 00:39:49.290
in America would not fall
below some threshold levels.

00:39:49.290 --> 00:39:52.590
So you could set some level
and say OK if you're poor,

00:39:52.590 --> 00:39:54.450
you know here's
this basic income.

00:39:54.450 --> 00:39:57.480
So I think that might more
interact with policies

00:39:57.480 --> 00:40:02.032
around welfare, or food stamps,
or the Earned Income Tax

00:40:02.032 --> 00:40:03.990
Credit, probably actually
the Earned Income Tax

00:40:03.990 --> 00:40:07.170
Credit, mostly would I
think be mostly affected

00:40:07.170 --> 00:40:09.720
if we started to think about
a universal basic income

00:40:09.720 --> 00:40:14.990
as a basic income for folks
that don't have a lot of income.

00:40:14.990 --> 00:40:18.780
And so I don't know so I
think it really-- that to

00:40:18.780 --> 00:40:23.010
me really is more about that
basic standard of living,

00:40:23.010 --> 00:40:25.830
whereas a lot of these policies
aren't so much about folks

00:40:25.830 --> 00:40:27.930
that don't have enough
to make ends meet

00:40:27.930 --> 00:40:30.090
or who aren't working.

00:40:30.090 --> 00:40:31.710
This is an agenda
for how does it

00:40:31.710 --> 00:40:34.317
that you make sure that you can
actually get people to work,

00:40:34.317 --> 00:40:36.150
and get them to work
in a way that's healthy

00:40:36.150 --> 00:40:38.220
and they're productive
and they're ready to go.

00:40:38.220 --> 00:40:41.970
And so conceptually, I think
it belongs in a different box.

00:40:41.970 --> 00:40:42.470
Right?

00:40:42.470 --> 00:40:44.136
Because even if you
have a basic income,

00:40:44.136 --> 00:40:47.880
that's not going to solve some
of your work life conflicts.

00:40:47.880 --> 00:40:49.249
So, yeah.

00:40:49.249 --> 00:40:50.790
AUDIENCE: So I was
interested to hear

00:40:50.790 --> 00:40:53.250
that a lot of the policies
that you describe in your book

00:40:53.250 --> 00:40:55.210
are being tried
in various states.

00:40:55.210 --> 00:40:57.510
So it's nice to have lots
of little experiments.

00:40:57.510 --> 00:41:00.000
What would you say about
the strength of the evidence

00:41:00.000 --> 00:41:02.220
for the different policies?

00:41:02.220 --> 00:41:04.689
And for the ones that have
really strong evidence, what

00:41:04.689 --> 00:41:06.480
are the big things that
are preventing them

00:41:06.480 --> 00:41:08.160
from being more widely adopted?

00:41:08.160 --> 00:41:10.620
HEATHER BOUSHEY: Yeah,
that's a fun question.

00:41:10.620 --> 00:41:12.640
Some of them don't
have any evidence,

00:41:12.640 --> 00:41:14.790
very much yet because the
policies are very new.

00:41:14.790 --> 00:41:17.520
So I would say on the stable
schedules legislation,

00:41:17.520 --> 00:41:18.970
we don't have evidence yet.

00:41:18.970 --> 00:41:21.620
And in fact my organization
the Washington Center

00:41:21.620 --> 00:41:24.441
for Equitable Growth, we
give grants to scholars.

00:41:24.441 --> 00:41:26.940
And we've been thinking a lot
about the scheduling stability

00:41:26.940 --> 00:41:29.430
piece, and how we can study
that and learn more about it.

00:41:29.430 --> 00:41:34.410
And we've funded a pilot study
that a couple of our scholars

00:41:34.410 --> 00:41:36.930
did with the gap, to
understand their move

00:41:36.930 --> 00:41:38.040
toward stable scheduling.

00:41:38.040 --> 00:41:39.040
And we've learned a lot.

00:41:39.040 --> 00:41:41.664
We're learning a lot from that.

00:41:41.664 --> 00:41:43.080
The gap is actually
felt that it's

00:41:43.080 --> 00:41:46.147
been quite effective, in
good for profitability,

00:41:46.147 --> 00:41:47.230
and good for productivity.

00:41:47.230 --> 00:41:49.620
And they've actually moved
forward on the policy.

00:41:49.620 --> 00:41:51.510
So we have some evidence
from some employers,

00:41:51.510 --> 00:41:53.850
but we don't have
evidence from a policy,

00:41:53.850 --> 00:41:58.329
from a state or local
government yet on that issue.

00:41:58.329 --> 00:41:59.620
There's two I want to touch on.

00:41:59.620 --> 00:42:03.240
One is on the child early
childhood development,

00:42:03.240 --> 00:42:04.730
and one on paid leave.

00:42:04.730 --> 00:42:07.380
And so on paid
family medical leave,

00:42:07.380 --> 00:42:10.230
we actually know quite
a bit about California.

00:42:10.230 --> 00:42:14.340
There were some in-depth
studies done in California

00:42:14.340 --> 00:42:18.210
around the implementation of
the paid family medical leave

00:42:18.210 --> 00:42:19.710
program here.

00:42:19.710 --> 00:42:25.020
And so we know, for example,
that 90% of employers

00:42:25.020 --> 00:42:29.610
in this survey reported that the
implementation of paid family

00:42:29.610 --> 00:42:31.350
medical leave here
in California,

00:42:31.350 --> 00:42:33.870
actually had no effect
or a positive effect

00:42:33.870 --> 00:42:36.252
on profitability
and productivity.

00:42:36.252 --> 00:42:36.960
That they didn't.

00:42:36.960 --> 00:42:39.900
So only 10% reported
any downside at all

00:42:39.900 --> 00:42:41.640
to the implementation.

00:42:41.640 --> 00:42:45.120
We also have good evidence on
what it did on the effects--

00:42:45.120 --> 00:42:47.280
on how it boosted
family incomes.

00:42:47.280 --> 00:42:49.530
We also know from that
research that a lot

00:42:49.530 --> 00:42:52.230
of people who are eligible for
paid leave here in California,

00:42:52.230 --> 00:42:53.520
haven't taken it.

00:42:53.520 --> 00:42:55.470
Disproportionately those
are low income folks

00:42:55.470 --> 00:42:57.330
who don't have job protection.

00:42:57.330 --> 00:43:01.410
So the paid-- so the federal
Family Medical Leave Act,

00:43:01.410 --> 00:43:05.220
gives you job protection to
take up to 12 weeks of leave

00:43:05.220 --> 00:43:07.410
to care for a new
child, an ailing loved

00:43:07.410 --> 00:43:08.880
one, or your own illness.

00:43:08.880 --> 00:43:10.620
Only about 60% of
the labor force

00:43:10.620 --> 00:43:13.590
is covered, however, because
if you haven't been at your job

00:43:13.590 --> 00:43:16.650
long enough, or if you work
for a very small employer

00:43:16.650 --> 00:43:18.877
you're not covered,
among other reasons.

00:43:18.877 --> 00:43:21.210
So a lot of the folks that
didn't take it in California,

00:43:21.210 --> 00:43:22.230
they didn't do it
because they were

00:43:22.230 --> 00:43:23.580
afraid of losing
their jobs or being

00:43:23.580 --> 00:43:24.820
punished by their employer.

00:43:24.820 --> 00:43:27.580
So that's a really
important data point.

00:43:27.580 --> 00:43:31.030
So we know a lot from
California and Equitable Growth

00:43:31.030 --> 00:43:35.562
has also funded some work
looking at other states.

00:43:35.562 --> 00:43:37.020
So we're learning
a lot from what's

00:43:37.020 --> 00:43:39.311
happening in Rhode Island,
New York and New Jersey that

00:43:39.311 --> 00:43:41.867
have implemented that program.

00:43:41.867 --> 00:43:43.950
Paid sick days, which I
wasn't going to talk about

00:43:43.950 --> 00:43:45.780
but since I'm here
in California.

00:43:45.780 --> 00:43:47.910
San Francisco was one
of the first places

00:43:47.910 --> 00:43:49.560
to implement paid sick days.

00:43:49.560 --> 00:43:51.230
And economists
went in and looked

00:43:51.230 --> 00:43:56.942
at what the outcome was on
employment, in San Francisco

00:43:56.942 --> 00:43:58.150
and the surrounding counties.

00:43:58.150 --> 00:43:59.800
Because one of the
arguments was, OK,

00:43:59.800 --> 00:44:02.734
if you give people the
right to earn up to,

00:44:02.734 --> 00:44:04.900
I believe it was seven days
of paid sick days in San

00:44:04.900 --> 00:44:06.620
Francisco, then that'll
be a job killer.

00:44:06.620 --> 00:44:07.120
Right?

00:44:07.120 --> 00:44:08.950
Obviously, people are going
to get laid off for that.

00:44:08.950 --> 00:44:10.491
That was the argument
that you heard.

00:44:10.491 --> 00:44:12.670
And in the book I
have some great quotes

00:44:12.670 --> 00:44:17.090
from employers who said that
before the legislation passed.

00:44:17.090 --> 00:44:19.660
But what these
economists found was

00:44:19.660 --> 00:44:22.750
that actually after the
legislation was put in place,

00:44:22.750 --> 00:44:26.770
employment in San Francisco
grew faster than the surrounding

00:44:26.770 --> 00:44:28.990
five counties in
like a year or two

00:44:28.990 --> 00:44:31.030
after the implementation
of the policy.

00:44:31.030 --> 00:44:33.610
And I am in no way saying that
the implementation of paid

00:44:33.610 --> 00:44:37.240
sick days caused the
greater employment gains.

00:44:37.240 --> 00:44:39.580
But it's a very difficult
threshold then to make

00:44:39.580 --> 00:44:42.340
the argument-- and this has been
replicated in other places--

00:44:42.340 --> 00:44:44.798
it's very difficult to make
the argument that giving people

00:44:44.798 --> 00:44:47.800
paid sick days pulled down jobs.

00:44:47.800 --> 00:44:49.914
When in fact, what
happened was the opposite.

00:44:49.914 --> 00:44:51.830
And this has happened
in other places as well.

00:44:51.830 --> 00:44:55.840
We have a similar study
in Seattle and in DC.

00:44:55.840 --> 00:44:58.930
And then on early
childhood, there

00:44:58.930 --> 00:45:01.780
is overwhelming
evidence at this point

00:45:01.780 --> 00:45:07.030
that not attending to
the years between 0 and 5

00:45:07.030 --> 00:45:11.260
has lifetime implications
for children.

00:45:11.260 --> 00:45:14.290
And again going to the economic
angle to our future labor

00:45:14.290 --> 00:45:15.260
supply.

00:45:15.260 --> 00:45:18.400
So we knew that the skills that
children enter kindergarten

00:45:18.400 --> 00:45:20.585
with, and the gaps
between children

00:45:20.585 --> 00:45:22.210
that have skills and
don't have skills,

00:45:22.210 --> 00:45:23.690
stay with them over a lifetime.

00:45:23.690 --> 00:45:25.970
And it's very difficult,
if not impossible,

00:45:25.970 --> 00:45:28.810
for later educational
interventions to really make up

00:45:28.810 --> 00:45:31.600
for those this early gaps.

00:45:31.600 --> 00:45:33.850
And yet we live in a
world where most women

00:45:33.850 --> 00:45:36.054
have their first child
before the age of 26.

00:45:36.054 --> 00:45:37.720
Young people don't
have a lot of income.

00:45:37.720 --> 00:45:40.160
They don't have access
to high quality care.

00:45:40.160 --> 00:45:41.832
And we do virtually nothing.

00:45:41.832 --> 00:45:43.540
We do some things for
very poor families,

00:45:43.540 --> 00:45:45.760
but we're not doing anything
for the vast majority

00:45:45.760 --> 00:45:48.640
of middle class families who
are really struggling to provide

00:45:48.640 --> 00:45:50.170
that high quality care.

00:45:50.170 --> 00:45:52.729
There is probably
no other investment

00:45:52.729 --> 00:45:54.520
that we could make in
America's future that

00:45:54.520 --> 00:45:56.500
would have as big a
bang for the buck,

00:45:56.500 --> 00:46:00.072
as investing in universal
child care and universal Pre-K.

00:46:00.072 --> 00:46:01.780
AUDIENCE: The second
part of the question

00:46:01.780 --> 00:46:08.110
was for policies like child
care policies, what's preventing

00:46:08.110 --> 00:46:10.456
their adoption more widely?

00:46:10.456 --> 00:46:11.830
HEATHER BOUSHEY:
Right of course.

00:46:11.830 --> 00:46:13.210
The grumpy part of the question.

00:46:13.210 --> 00:46:15.160
Where, you know, the why
isn't that happening?

00:46:15.160 --> 00:46:18.004
So yeah, of course this is so
great, why isn't it happening?

00:46:18.004 --> 00:46:19.420
So I mean I will
say a few things.

00:46:19.420 --> 00:46:23.192
I mean one is that you've seen a
lot of employers moving forward

00:46:23.192 --> 00:46:25.150
in implementing these
policies, where they can.

00:46:25.150 --> 00:46:28.660
So that's a sign that people
are getting the message on this.

00:46:28.660 --> 00:46:30.280
Not nearly enough
and not across all

00:46:30.280 --> 00:46:33.640
of their workers, which
I think is a problem.

00:46:33.640 --> 00:46:37.870
Second, I do want to stress that
this is one area where you've

00:46:37.870 --> 00:46:42.110
seen really remarkable social
change over the past decade.

00:46:42.110 --> 00:46:48.162
So even amidst a lot of
lack of progressive movement

00:46:48.162 --> 00:46:49.870
in places around the
country on policies,

00:46:49.870 --> 00:46:52.190
this is really a bright spot.

00:46:52.190 --> 00:46:55.420
We've implemented universal
social insurance programs

00:46:55.420 --> 00:46:57.730
in four states, in
the past decade, which

00:46:57.730 --> 00:46:59.170
is an amazing accomplishment.

00:46:59.170 --> 00:47:03.490
So, and then it's passed
and a couple of others

00:47:03.490 --> 00:47:04.960
but hasn't been implemented yet.

00:47:04.960 --> 00:47:07.390
So I think that there is
a lot of forward momentum.

00:47:07.390 --> 00:47:08.590
And then all the
places that have done

00:47:08.590 --> 00:47:09.800
paid sick days and the like.

00:47:09.800 --> 00:47:11.950
And places like DC
and other places that

00:47:11.950 --> 00:47:14.650
have universal Pre-K. We
have free universal Pre-K

00:47:14.650 --> 00:47:16.490
in the District of Columbia.

00:47:16.490 --> 00:47:17.920
So I think that's positive.

00:47:17.920 --> 00:47:20.230
At the federal level,
I mean certainly what

00:47:20.230 --> 00:47:23.240
you see is these
issues, like all issues,

00:47:23.240 --> 00:47:25.240
have been affected by the
continued polarization

00:47:25.240 --> 00:47:26.320
and gridlock.

00:47:26.320 --> 00:47:29.290
But what I will say is that
the 2016 campaign cycle

00:47:29.290 --> 00:47:32.950
was the first one where you saw
presidential candidates on both

00:47:32.950 --> 00:47:35.200
the left and the right
come out in favor

00:47:35.200 --> 00:47:36.950
of pieces of this agenda.

00:47:36.950 --> 00:47:41.085
So you had Marco Rubio,
Republican Marco Rubio,

00:47:41.085 --> 00:47:42.710
who came out with a
paid leave program.

00:47:42.710 --> 00:47:46.750
You had Secretary Clinton
who had a full agenda on all

00:47:46.750 --> 00:47:47.890
of these issues.

00:47:47.890 --> 00:47:50.350
You had Bernie Sanders who
signed onto the Family Act,

00:47:50.350 --> 00:47:52.360
to provide paid
family medical leave.

00:47:52.360 --> 00:47:54.970
And you had now
President Trump who

00:47:54.970 --> 00:47:57.280
came out with policies
around child care

00:47:57.280 --> 00:47:59.560
and maternity leave
during the campaign.

00:47:59.560 --> 00:48:01.930
And then on Tuesday in
his speech to Congress,

00:48:01.930 --> 00:48:03.670
actually talked about
paid family leave

00:48:03.670 --> 00:48:04.780
and paid parental leave.

00:48:04.780 --> 00:48:07.560
So and he-- and I actually
can't remember if he--

00:48:07.560 --> 00:48:11.620
I believe he also mentioned
childcare is a part of his tax

00:48:11.620 --> 00:48:12.560
program as well.

00:48:12.560 --> 00:48:15.580
So you're actually seeing
these bubbling up and getting

00:48:15.580 --> 00:48:17.200
traction across the aisle.

00:48:17.200 --> 00:48:20.980
So I actually think of all
of the different policy areas

00:48:20.980 --> 00:48:22.525
that I can work on
as an economist.

00:48:22.525 --> 00:48:23.900
I actually think
this is probably

00:48:23.900 --> 00:48:26.680
one of the most hopeful ones,
where there is a greater,

00:48:26.680 --> 00:48:29.080
the greatest potential
to really see

00:48:29.080 --> 00:48:31.960
the kind of transformational
change over the next decade,

00:48:31.960 --> 00:48:35.330
because you've seen
it in so many places.

00:48:35.330 --> 00:48:38.340
So, and then why hasn't
it moved as quickly.

00:48:38.340 --> 00:48:41.860
I actually think that
it's been good to see

00:48:41.860 --> 00:48:44.620
these policies implemented
at the state and local level,

00:48:44.620 --> 00:48:47.470
so folks like myself and people
I work with could actually

00:48:47.470 --> 00:48:50.350
take the time to study
it, and know what works

00:48:50.350 --> 00:48:53.050
and what doesn't, at the
laboratories of democracy

00:48:53.050 --> 00:48:54.370
kind of idea.

00:48:54.370 --> 00:48:55.870
And I think we're
getting to a place

00:48:55.870 --> 00:48:57.880
where we know so much
about some of these,

00:48:57.880 --> 00:49:00.590
that we really are ready to
move those at the federal level.

00:49:00.590 --> 00:49:02.320
So we will see.

00:49:02.320 --> 00:49:04.986
I'm not terribly
optimistic that these

00:49:04.986 --> 00:49:06.860
are going to be prioritized
by this Congress,

00:49:06.860 --> 00:49:08.710
but hope springs eternal.

00:49:12.200 --> 00:49:16.280
AUDIENCE: Have you studied the
opposite phenomena of families

00:49:16.280 --> 00:49:21.560
trying to combine a quality care
and more time for the family

00:49:21.560 --> 00:49:26.510
by moving out of
the salaried work

00:49:26.510 --> 00:49:30.835
place into consulting or
even into to home child care.

00:49:30.835 --> 00:49:32.210
HEATHER BOUSHEY:
So when you look

00:49:32.210 --> 00:49:34.800
at the overall trends
in labor supply,

00:49:34.800 --> 00:49:38.640
you see a flattening off since
the late 1990s for both men

00:49:38.640 --> 00:49:39.140
and women.

00:49:39.140 --> 00:49:40.514
Of course there
was the deep dive

00:49:40.514 --> 00:49:43.000
during the Great Recession,
and then bubbling back up.

00:49:43.000 --> 00:49:46.400
But the United States now
has lower labor supply

00:49:46.400 --> 00:49:49.627
than most of our economic
competitors in the OECD.

00:49:49.627 --> 00:49:50.960
We used to be among the highest.

00:49:50.960 --> 00:49:54.590
Now we're among the lowest
for both men and women.

00:49:54.590 --> 00:49:57.380
So that may be kind of
connected to your question,

00:49:57.380 --> 00:50:01.430
that folks are unable to sort
of deal with the conflicts

00:50:01.430 --> 00:50:03.080
around work and life, you know.

00:50:03.080 --> 00:50:07.100
I tell in the book a lot of
stories of people in their 50s,

00:50:07.100 --> 00:50:09.680
in later life who end up
dropping out of the labor force

00:50:09.680 --> 00:50:11.720
to care for an ailing
parent, and then

00:50:11.720 --> 00:50:13.654
find it really difficult
to get back in.

00:50:13.654 --> 00:50:15.320
So maybe they do part
time work, or they

00:50:15.320 --> 00:50:18.320
take on some consulting,
or some bits and pieces.

00:50:18.320 --> 00:50:20.342
The stories-- I
mean I think what

00:50:20.342 --> 00:50:22.550
I see because a lot of that
is happening at the lower

00:50:22.550 --> 00:50:26.840
end, at the middle to
bottom, it's less about, oh,

00:50:26.840 --> 00:50:28.190
this is great for me.

00:50:28.190 --> 00:50:30.530
It's more about, oh well,
this is really all I can do,

00:50:30.530 --> 00:50:32.260
given my situation.

00:50:32.260 --> 00:50:35.090
And because I can't find an
employer that will be flexible.

00:50:35.090 --> 00:50:37.730
So I think there's a
negative story there.

00:50:37.730 --> 00:50:39.230
But I think certainly,
and this gets

00:50:39.230 --> 00:50:41.390
to the question over
here about consumption,

00:50:41.390 --> 00:50:43.460
you certainly see
some conversations

00:50:43.460 --> 00:50:45.470
at the top about how
much families need,

00:50:45.470 --> 00:50:48.230
and can they downsize, and
can they kind of pare back

00:50:48.230 --> 00:50:51.740
to deal with some of
these care issues.

00:50:51.740 --> 00:50:55.370
And I don't think you--
so you don't see a pulling

00:50:55.370 --> 00:50:56.930
back in labor force
participation,

00:50:56.930 --> 00:50:59.480
but you see a leveling
off of the increase.

00:50:59.480 --> 00:51:01.250
So it may be that
those folks that,

00:51:01.250 --> 00:51:04.040
were we to have this
kind of policy agenda,

00:51:04.040 --> 00:51:06.020
might actually increase
their labor supply,

00:51:06.020 --> 00:51:07.100
aren't actually doing so.

00:51:07.100 --> 00:51:08.420
So that's an effect as well.

00:51:08.420 --> 00:51:11.539
But it's not actually a
pulling back, but a flattening.

